## Ensemble Learning


Ensemble Methods

* Voting, Bagging, Boosting, Stacking

* Voting and bagging involves numerous classifiers making predictions by voting

* Voting utilizes different classifiers whilst bagging utilizes one classifier

* Random forest is a popular bagging method (It actually performs quite well)

<table border="1" class="dataframe">
  <thead>
    <tr style="text-align: right;">
      <th></th>
      <th>Bagging</th>
      <th>Boosting</th>
      <th>Stacking</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <th>Purpose</th>
      <td>Reduce Variance</td>
      <td>Reduce Bias</td>
      <td>Improev Accuracy</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>Base Learner Types</th>
      <td>Homogeneous</td>
      <td>Homogeneous</td>
      <td>Heterogeneous</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>Base Learner Training</th>
      <td>Parallel</td>
      <td>Sequential</td>
      <td>Metal Model</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>Aggregation</th>
      <td>Max Voting, Averaging</td>
      <td>Weighted Averaging</td>
      <td>Weighted Averaging</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


```python
import pandas as pd 

wine = pd.read_csv("wine.csv", index_col=0)
wine.head()

wine['taste'] = [1 if grade >5 else 0 for grade in wine['quality']]
X = wine.drop(['quality', 'taste'], axis=1)
y = wine['taste'].values.reshape(-1)

wine.head()
```

```python
from sklearn.ensemble import (AdaBoostClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier, 
                              RandomForestClassifier)
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier 
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
```


```python
models = []
models.append(('AdaBoostClassifier', AdaBoostClassifier()))
models.append(('GradientBoostingClassifier', GradientBoostingClassifier()))
models.append(('RandomForestClassifier', RandomForestClassifier()))
models.append(('DecisionTreeClassifier', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
models.append(('LogisticRegression', LogisticRegression()))
```


```python
models
```

 ('RandomForestClassifier', RandomForestClassifier()),

 ('LogisticRegression', LogisticRegression())]
</pre>

```python
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score

results = []
names = []

for name, model in models: # I can just iterate over a list of tuples like this
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=5, random_state= 13, shuffle=True)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, 
                                 cv=kfold,
                                 scoring='accuracy')
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)

    print(name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
```

### AdaBoost

*All pics from StatQuest*



A node and two leaves is called a stump.

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/c1fBqz/btqyET9Bdij/wZtw6tawkvAaKzP8AMMjC0/img.png) 



AdaBoost consists of several stumps which is called a 'Forest of Stumps'

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/x99kf/btqyGctSY69/ZhVKLbLLC9oY80I5KFX2ZK/img.png)



Unlike trees, stumps cannot make accurate classifications. Stumps can only make classifications based on one question. Therefore we can say that a stump is a 'weak learner'.

A random Forest model combines multiple trees with an equal weight.

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/bdooL9/btqyFZIjDZF/Kiec41mogTObPcoqTswJp0/img.png)



In adaboost certain stumps are given greater weight than others. We say that stumps with greaterweights have a higher 'Amount of Say'. 

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/tx4Xf/btqyGxj3Ofx/jTjNykKTmmrP7DjEpY5Si0/img.png)

Moreover, the error of the first stump affects the second and the error of the second affects the third so forth... 




#### The Three Main Ideas  Behind AdaBoost 

1) AdaBoost combines a lot of "weak learners' to make classifications. The weak learner are almost always stumps. 

2) Some stumps get more say in the classification than others. 

3) Each stump is made by taking the previous stump's mistakes into account.



#### How AdaBoost Makes Predictions

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/BuZ4v/btqyOoGTeIY/zXcMRrAUJfxk1MqI6Ey19k/img.png)

Sample weight is set as 1/(total number of samples). Then we observe the effect of each feature on the target value(Heart Disease). 

The relationship between Chest Pain and Heart Disease

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/RM6St/btqyLJkY2fk/FC2fB2GbgnoNukJ0PFRo70/img.png)



Now let's take a look at the relationship between Blocked Arteries and Heart Disease 

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/4afGh/btqyLKRGCNd/TiECwfUEqftoedmBOxNeHk/img.png)



Lastly, the relationship between Patient Weight and Heart Disease

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/cdLq4T/btqyOngWsfl/PFtDn19884g2sB1Wki07mk/img.png)



We can now calculate the gini index of each stump 

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/VQb9u/btqyN334J67/v9QoDiX1PGKntKCzV3Fyd0/img.png)

As the last stump has the smallest gini index, we set the last stump as the first stump. 

#### Calculating the Amount of Say

$Amount of Say = \frac{1}{2}log(\frac{1- Total Error}{Total Error})$

The last stump only incorrectly classified one observation. Therefore, the total error is 1/8. 

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/OGgMI/btqyLKK1rUc/KVKjGzwXLisG8HZ3MB06MK/img.png)



The following graph is the Amount of Say plotted against the total error. If the total error is 0 that means correct classification whilst a total error of 1 would lead to an extremely low Amount of Say. If the total error is 0.5 the amount of say will be 0, meaning that the stump is no better than flipping a coin. 

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/c2v7ec/btqyMrRViSc/AzZqB4fpkqXGqmfe2ciebK/img.png)

The total error for the stump is 1/8 so the Amount of Say is, 

$Amount of Say = \frac{1}{2}log(\frac{1 - 1/8}{1/8}) = 0.97$

![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/RBEZr/btqyKIAiXSG/gr6jtUzKTub3udRFVLIrG0/img.png)



#### Setting the New Sample Weight 

In Adaboost the sample which a stump misclassified gets a greater weight before being passed to the next stump. 



![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/ciEAVZ/btqyOnuQNzN/KnKjaZLRSr5XJSHROTZMY0/img.png)

The new sample weight of the misclassified observation becomes 0.33 whilst the weights of the correctly classified observations become 0.05



![img](https://blog.kakaocdn.net/dn/dWsSbi/btqyOogaTc4/CTxu4GX9aydifBiDwi2KSK/img.png)

We can normalize the weights by dividing the weights by the total weight 

### GBM Gradient Boosting Machine

* 부스팅 알고리즘은 여러 개의 약한 학습기 (Weak learner)를 순차적으로 학습-예측하면서 잘못 예측한 데이터에 가중치를 부여해서 오류를 개선해가는 방식 

* GBM은 가중치를 업데이트할 때 경사 하강법(Gradient Descent)를 사용



```python
import pandas as pd 

feature_name_df = pd.read_csv("features.txt", sep='\s+', header=None, 
                           index_col=None)
feature_name = feature_name_df.iloc[:, 1].values.tolist()

X_train = pd.read_csv('X_train.txt', sep='\s+', header=None)
X_test = pd.read_csv('X_test.txt', sep='\s+', header=None)

X_train.columns = feature_name
X_test.columns = feature_name 
```


```python
y_train = pd.read_csv('y_train.txt', sep='\s+', header=None, names=['action'])
y_test = pd.read_csv('y_test.txt', sep='\s+', header=None, names=['action'])
```


```python
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier 
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import time
import warnings 

warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
```


```python
start_time = time.time()

gb_clf = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=13)
gb_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
gb_pred = gb_clf.predict(X_test)

print('ACC : ', accuracy_score(y_test, gb_pred) )
```

* 일반적으로 GBM이 성능자체는 랜덤 포레스트보다는 좋다고 알려져 있음

* Scikit-learn의 GBM은 속도가 아주 느림



```python
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

params = { 
    'n_estimators': [100, 500], #Number of decision trees
    'learning_rate' : [0.05,0.1]
}

grid = GridSearchCV(gb_clf, param_grid=params, cv=2, verbose=1, 
                    n_jobs=-1)
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
```

### XGBoost 

* 트리 기반의 앙상블 학습에서 가장 각광받는 알고리즘 중 하나 

* GBM 기반의 알고리즘인제 GBM의 느린 속도를 다양한 규제를 통해 해결 

* 특히 병렬 학습이 가능하도록 설계됨 

* XGBoost는 반복 수행 시마다 내부적으로 학습데이터와 검증데이터를 교차검증

* 교차검증을 통해 최적화되면 반복을 중단하는 조기 중단 기능을 가지고 있음


#### Major Parameters

* nthread: CPU의 실행 스레드 개수를 조정. 디폴트는 CPU의 전체 스레드를 사용하는 것 

* eta: GBM 학습률 

* num_boost_rounds: n_estimators와 같은 파라미터 

* max_depth

* scikit 유저들을 위해 파라미터를 그대로 쓸 수 있게 해놨다



```python
from xgboost import XGBClassifier 

xgb = XGBClassifier(n_estimators = 400, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3)
#number of trees, learning rate, max_depth 

#xgboost는 무조건 넘파이 어레이로 
```

```python
from sklearn.metrics import (accuracy_score, precision_score, 
                             recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score)

def get_clf_eval(y_test, pred): 
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, pred)
    pre = precision_score(y_test, pred)
    re = recall_score(y_test, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, pred)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, pred)

    return acc, pre, re, f1, auc
```


```python
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix 

def print_clf_eval(y_test, pred):
    confusion = confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)
    acc, pre, re, f1, auc = get_clf_eval(y_test, pred)

    print('==> Confusion matrix')
    print(confusion)
    print('===================')

    print('Accuracy : {0:.4f}, precision : {1:.4f}'.format(acc, pre))
    print('Recall : {0:.4f}, F1 : {1:.4f}, AUC: {2:.4f}'.format(re, f1, auc))
```

#### 여기서 Recall과 Precision의 의미는 

* 은행 입장에서는 Recall이 좋을 것이다 

* 사용자 입장에서는 Precision이 좋다 

* 사용자 입장에서는 Recall이 높아지면 정상 사용자가 귀찮아질 수도 있다



```python
def get_result(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred = model.predict(X_test)

    return get_clf_eval(y_test, pred)
```


```python
def get_result_pd(models, model_names, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    col_names = ['Accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1', 'roc_auc']
    tmp = []

    for model in models:
        tmp.append(get_result(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test))
    
    return pd.DataFrame(tmp, columns=col_names, index=model_names)
```



#### 모델별 ROC 커브



```python
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve 

def draw_roc_curve(models, model_names, X_test, y_test):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

    for model in range(len(models)):
        pred = models[model].predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, pred)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=model_names[model])
    
    plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], 'k--', label='random guess')
    plt.title('ROC')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid()

draw_roc_curve(models, model_names, X_test, y_test)
```

* 우선 fraud data에 대해서만 outlier 확인 



```python
def get_outlier(df=None, column=None, weight=1.5): 
    fraud = df[df['Class'] == 1][column]

    quantile_25 = np.percentile(fraud.values, 25)
    quantile_75 = np.percentile(fraud.values, 75)

    iqr = quantile_75 - quantile_25 
    iqr_weight = iqr * weight 

    lowest_val = quantile_25 - iqr_weight 
    highest_val = quantile_75 + iqr_weight 

    outlier_index = fraud[(fraud < lowest_val) | (fraud > highest_val)].index

    return outlier_index 
```

```python
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve 

def draw_roc_curve(models, model_names, X_test, y_test):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

    for model in range(len(models)):
        pred = models[model].predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, pred)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=model_names[model])
    
    plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], 'k--', label='random guess')
    plt.title('ROC')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid()

draw_roc_curve(models, model_names, X_test, y_test)
```
